Part 1: The Three Pillars (The Core Libraries)
At the very top of the code, three main engines are imported. Here is what they actually do:

1. PyQt6.QtWidgets (The Physical Bricks & Mortar)

Definition: This library builds every single physical, tangible element seen on the screen.
Buttons, text boxes, tables, popups—these are all widgets.

Implementation: The physical structure and furniture of the application are built entirely out of this library.

2. PyQt6.QtGui (The Paint & Decor)

Definition: "Gui" here refers to graphical utilities. This library is used for aesthetics—adding
icons, changing fonts, and drawing on the screen. It doesn't build the physical box; it paints and decorates the box.

Implementation: Used to attach small icons (like the magnifying glass) and abstract commands to the application.

3. PyQt6.QtCore (The Nervous System & Physics)

Definition: This is the background engine. There is nothing visual here. It handles how the app runs in memory,
 the underlying event loops, data formats, and core system rules.

Implementation: Used for Qt.MatchFlag.MatchFixedString, which is a core rule telling the database/table
 search engine exactly how to process and match text.

Part 2: The QtGui Classes (The Aesthetics)

QAction:

Definition: This is not a physical button. It is an "Abstract Command." It defines the name of
 a task and what should happen when it is triggered.

Implementation: The add_student_action acts as this abstract command. It could be attached to a
top Menu bar (File > Add Student) or a Toolbar icon. QAction is the logic that can be plugged in anywhere in the UI.

QIcon:

Definition: Takes a raw image file (png/jpg) and converts it into a standardized icon format
 that PyQt can understand and render natively.

Implementation: Used to load the magnifying glass and plus sign images for the "Search" and "Add" actions.

Part 3: The QtWidgets Classes (The Physical Blocks)
These are the building blocks glued together to build the Student Management System,
categorized by their actual architectural function.

Group A: The Base Containers (The Land & Rooms)

QApplication:

Definition: The Master Power Switch. This starts the core event loop of the application,
 constantly listening for mouse clicks and keystrokes. Without this, the GUI is dead code.

Implementation: Initialized at the bottom with app = QApplication(sys.argv) and keeps the
engine running with app.exec().

QMainWindow:

Definition: The Main Building. This is a special, heavy-duty container that comes with
 pre-reserved slots for a Menu Bar, Tool Bar, and Status Bar.

Implementation: The main class inherits from this, placing the large data table right in its center.

QDialog:

Definition: A temporary popup room. It is not a primary window; it opens to grab attention,
collects input, executes a specific task, and then destroys itself.

Implementation: Separate QDialog popups handle inserting, searching, editing, and deleting students.

Group B: Data Interaction (Showing & Collecting Data)

QTableWidget:

Definition: An Excel-like grid structure containing rows and columns.

Implementation: Placed on the main screen to display the master list of students fetched from the database.

QTableWidgetItem:

Definition: A single, isolated cell inside the table. QTableWidget is just the skeleton;
every single box inside it holding text is a QTableWidgetItem.

Implementation: The loop iterates through database results, packs every single piece of data into one of these items,
and injects it into the table using .setItem().

QLineEdit:

Definition: A single-line blank input box where characters are physically typed using a keyboard.

Implementation: Used to collect raw text for the Name and Mobile number fields.

QComboBox:

Definition: A dropdown menu. It restricts free typing and forces a selection from a predefined list.

Implementation: Used for selecting Subjects (Math, Biology, Physics). This is smart engineering—it prevents
 spelling mistakes that would crash database queries.

Group C: Interaction & Feedback (Buttons & Text)

QPushButton:

Definition: A standard, physical, clickable button.


Implementation: Creates the "Submit", "Search", "Update", "Yes", and "No" buttons.

QLabel:

Definition: Static, read-only text or imagery glued to the screen. It cannot be edited.

Implementation: Used as headers above input boxes ("Name:", "Mobile:") and for asking confirmation ("Are you sure?").

QMessageBox:

Definition: A pre-built, standardized popup box. There is no need to build the layout for this.
 It is specifically designed to flash warnings, errors, or success alerts.

Implementation: Used for the "About" dialog and to flash the "Success" message after a record is deleted.

Group D: Accessories (Peripheral Features)

QToolBar:

Definition: A horizontal strip typically at the top of the main window designed to hold quick-access shortcut icons.

Implementation: Used to house the "Add Student" and "Search" shortcut actions.

QStatusBar:

Definition: A horizontal strip at the very bottom of the main window used for temporary
 system updates or contextual controls.

Implementation: A clever workaround injects the "Edit" and "Delete" buttons into this
 bottom strip dynamically when a cell is clicked.

Group E: The Skeletons (Invisible Layouts)

QVBoxLayout (Vertical Box Layout):

Definition: An invisible structural framework that stacks widgets strictly top-to-bottom
 in a straight vertical line.

Implementation: Used in the Edit and Search dialogs to neatly stack input boxes and buttons one below the other.

QGridLayout:

Definition: Invisible graph paper. Widgets are mapped to exact coordinate positions
(row, column)—like (0,0) or (0,1).

Implementation: Used in the Delete dialog and the previous Age Calculator, where labels
 and input boxes must be placed neatly side-by-side.